[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Planning a new test**\n\nI need to write a new test, and I think I could just instantiate the necessary components to cover the behavior I need. I’ll keep it outside the main package and avoid hardcoding any versions. The test should not rely on direct reflection but instead should assert how cookies are handled regarding credentials. I’ll focus only on the active class for this. That sounds like a good plan!\n\n**Examining class initialization**\n\nWhen the `HttpState` is initialized, it will trigger the static initializer for `class$`. However, I'm not importing `HttpState.class`, and instead, I'm creating a new `HttpState` instance in the method, which seems fine. \n\nI need to ensure a one-to-one mapping with the `HttpStateTest` class. A potential concern is that the Native Image class initializes at build time, so accessing `Class.forName` might not work at runtime. Tests under the Native Image by default might not cover everything, but I think new `HttpState` instances will be initialized during test runtime, helping us cover the necessary areas.\n\n**Considering native image initialization**\n\nIn a native image context, class initialization likely happens at build time because it tends to be safer. However, I'm skeptical about commons logging being safe. The existing build arguments only cover basics like the header. If `HttpState` is indeed built at compile time, the tests should still work fine. Coverage will probably be handled by the JVM, which is okay. I need to focus on writing the tests and familiarizing myself with AssertJ and reading the `Cookie` source for its constructors.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_05bf765d4c36a6fd016a047fcf0dcc819eb28ca3ca4ef46a64\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqBH_Yj9I2nm6NRaMxcAnVxyFotZdyIe7vuluxZ2WWoNh_ABYpJPm_rhtG6vR__rn_BsBsx_v1BgACUuqJIpKk_H3hBepAlUUpv3yEJhJkBaZ7NFA3uWPjFARVioQqIPM